Shot for @les_vergers_boiron_americas @guittardchocolate, filmed with @iamcardib and @miyokoscreamery, wrote a lot, consulted a lot, broke free of Beverly Hills, raised some money, had a ton of fun and ready for 2023! Here is a preview: I’m teaching in Stockholm, Buffalo and Los Angeles. I’m going to France for training, visiting a friend in Antwerp to learn how to make giant speculoos, and visiting a cacao plantation in Vietnam. Why am I doing all of that? Because I need to prepare myself for the opening of two new chocolate brands…Insha’allah.

Zone temping my chocolate kitchen is important so I can mark my coated pieces correctly. I’ll have my enrobing line in one room and the cooling tunnel in another. This gives me the opportunity to keep the machine in a room that’s 24°c so I can apply structure sheets, transfers and marks on the chocolate before it sets before they go through a wall and into a cooling tunnel. When they come out of a cooling tunnel, they can be packed in a room kept at 18°c.

When I first heard that Swedes love salted black licorice, I thought, “Man, this is a country that needs to try yuzu.” Then I tasted it. Wow. It’s shocking at first; it tastes like salty muscovado and molasses. It quickly grew on me. This truffle had a beautiful texture too. I also tried the salt used to season it. It’s not like anything I’ve tasted. It was so intense that it was almost dangerous. But I want to taste it again. People always ask me why I don’t eat my own food. It’s simple; I know what it tastes like. I want to taste something from another culture. It challenges me. I am not sure that I could turn Americans on to it or at least not to this intensity but it is so good. It’s even better with raspberry, strawberry and white chocolate. Truffle by @chefjungstedt

Someone asked me why I always send one through first. That’s an easy answer: I’m testing the air blade speed, the detail rod and the tap. Chocolate machines have to be dialed in. They are engineered to be dialed in for different products. For this bar, we had to change the bottoming tray so it was deeper and we had to slow the belt to get proper coating. And I want the fan to be just right so I can see the dried fruits under the chocolate coating that tantalizes the customer so that they purchase it.

😃😃😃😃 I’m testing new recipes and techniques and this weekend kicked it off. Lauren and I spent the weekend playing with new chocolates, new chocolate moulds, new steps but primarily we worked on new gianduja. I’m not a one trick pony and I didn’t leave my best behind at my last job. Not even close. This is a total departure from what I did. I want at least five variety of gianduja as part of my lineup so we tested and took detailed notes down to the amount of salt used to the overage as we dial in the recipes. We used almond and milk chocolate gianduja and dark hazelnut gianduja and prepared the same recipe with both. Each recipe includes caramel with salted butter, orange, vanilla and cinnamon from Vietnam 🇻🇳 (hello fam). The second almond gianduja was prepared with baked, ground nougatine and a hazelnut praline ganache. All of these are incredible. Next, we coat and work on the motif.

I’m often asked about what guitar to buy. Tht’s an easy answer; I only use @dedy_gmbh. You can find them on my Amazon page @shopkrissharvey and follow the link. Lightweight, easy to string, easy to clean. But let me offer you more knowledge; the base comes in two sizes and that determines what sizes that you can cut. This is a 5 mm base and they make a 7.5 mm base. That means the solid metal part and the gap between measures either 5 mm or 7.5 mm. Each cut is a multiplication of that number. So you can cut 15, 20,25 and 30 mm on the 5 mm base and you can cut 15, 22.5, 30 and 37.5 mm on the 7.5 mm base. Get it? Class dismissed.

I want to start a new trend in chocolate; I want to get back to making chocolate actually taste like chocolate. One of the principles of my new company is to feature single origin, single sourced or single estate chocolates, simply enrobed in black or milk chocolate. I’ll feature black and milk chocolate ganaches from the same plantation born in Viet Nam. I will have the same ability to feature ganaches made with wild Bolivian cacao beans. And I’ll be using single estate chocolate from Hawaii as shown here. There will not be any marshmallows, jelly or anything else mixed with these chocolates that would sully the purity. You’ll be able to taste chocolate with all of it beautiful nuance.

There is something so magical about what we do as chefs. It’s really more an evolution of what we do as humans. We’ve been blessed by Mother Nature and that she has given us the ability to identify what is edible and what isn’t. From there, we adapt to what is available. In most cases, it’s based on where you were born and to what culture you were raised in. Koreans eat kimchi almost daily. It was created to keep people alive who otherwise would have died from starvation. Now, it’s looked at as a common dish. As a young pastry cook, I didn’t care about what the bread bakers were doing. They’d talk with great respect about their levain and their dough. “It’s alive man. Don’t you get it? It’s a living thing.” I’d dismiss it because I was too busy focusing on the beauty of the exterior of what I was doing. I changed my mind many years ago. Dough is fascinating. Like chocolate, we can manipulate it to a point but it’s also our master. When it tells us it’s ready for the next stage, it takes a human to get it there. As soon as I made this dough, the clock in my head started. It was on the table for 45 minutes before I put it to bed for the evening. 45 minutes for it to come to life! It’s my duty to treat it with respect.

I never post anything on my account that isn’t of my creation and execution. This is the one exception because the opportunity to taste a pink praline tart is so rare. I’m now obsessed and I plan on creating my own. These are only available in Lyon and I was lucky enough to try the perfect version of this made by pâtissier Nicolas Pépin @maisonpepinlyon. The tart is made by using classic Saint Genix candied pink almonds with a sandy finish. Sometimes they are polished with Lac resin but it’s not typical. The almonds are coated in a pink syrup that evaporates as it’s cooked and then they become sandy. The almonds are crushed and cooked with heavy cream before being poured into a baked Sablé shell. After setting, it’s ready to eat. I’ve wanted to try this my entire career. A true regional speciality of France, Mr. Pépin won an award last year for the best praline in Lyon. The key to cut the sweetness is a properly baked shell and nuts that are well roasted. Liberté, égalité, fraternité.

I’ve been a customer of @les_vergers_boiron since 1993. I’ve used tens of thousands of kilos of their fruit pulp but I’ve never visited their growers. Last week, I was lucky enough to visit the orchard in Bollène that grows the pear, Granny Smith apple and kiwi 🥝 used for their purée. I’ve been asked if it was strange that they grow kiwi. Southeastern France is similar to the central coast of California. It’s very warm and dry and perfect for growing a variety of fruits. As I walked through the rows of pear trees, I noticed that they were all picked. The remaining pears on the ground were all fermenting and the air smelled like Poire Williams (Williams is the variety of pear used for Boiron). Some fruits show obvious signs of ripeness; banana, passion fruit and berries for example. Some fruits, like apple, ripen on the trees. Pears aren’t allowed to ripen on the tree. So how do they get the entire yield ripe? We drove across the street where the pears are washed and ripened. They are placed in a cold room in bins and periodically checked with a device called a Penetrometer. It measures the amount of pressure it takes to penetrate the fruit in kilograms. That tells the gentleman in the video just how ripe the fruit is. You can hear him say that it’s measuring at 8 kg. That’s unacceptable and he needs to get it between 1 and 2 kilograms of pressure on average before the fruit is processed and sent to you so that you can make sorbet, pâte de fruit, coulis, mousse etc.

RECIPE ALERT! The holidays are here and it’s time to give gifts of food to your friends and share with your loved ones. Today is extra special because it was two years ago today that I proposed to Hiền! So we made this quince jelly that you can eat with cheese, nuts and bread. I selected  Tomme de Savoie, a mild cows cheese from the French Alps ❤️ and I used the delicious quince pulp from @les_vergers_boiron @les_vergers_boiron_americas Ready to cook? Let’s go! 

1 kg Quince purée Les Vergers Boiron 

100 g granulated sugar
12 g yellow pectin e440 

970 g sugar 
120 g glucose syrup 60 DE (regular corn syrup will work)

30 g citric acid solution (50/50 acid powder and water) 

1. Warm the pulp to 50° C. 
2. Mix the first sugar with the pectin and whisk into the warm pulp. Boil for 30 seconds.
3. Add the glucose syrup and return to a boil.
4. Add the sugar in four increments allowing to recover to a boil between additions. 
5. Cook to 74/75 brix or about 105° C. 
6. Add the acid and boil for ten seconds. 
7. Pour into containers. Allow to set,slice and enjoy! Keep covered at ambiance.

When I was a young pastry cook and wannabe chocolatier, I made the mistake of falling in love with all of the many shapes of chocolate moulds that I would see in the catalogues that were dropped off by the chocolate reps. As I teach and consult, I listen to my students and clients and I see them going down the same rabbit hole. And who can resist? All of the shapes certainly are beautiful. But falling in love with moulds that have sharp edges in the cavities, corners and tiny negative spots can create issues when coloring. They are also difficult to polish (use cotton make up pads and 91% isopropyl alcohol). I use exclusively @chocolateworldantwerp 2022 (with the exception of holidays like Valentine’s Day). The hemisphere shape is easy to polish to get the optimal shine and easy to decorate from the inside out and spray. The other key is the frame of 2022 has 40 cavities. Other moulds only have 28 cavities. As I plan my opening, I’m using a fine lens to look at every step so I save money. Deciding to go forward with this shape made sense financially in three ways; I buy less moulds than a frame that has just 28 cavities, I have a higher yield for less effort and it’s the same price as a mould that has 28 cavities. Plus, my signature straight lines look super hot when you open the box. When you plan, look at every angle.
